Cybercrime Type: UPI / Online Payment Fraud

The Fake Customer Care Refund Scam
What Is This Crime?
UPI (Unified Payments Interface) fraud is a form of financial cybercrime in which attackers manipulate victims into authorising money transfers from their own bank accounts — typically by impersonating customer care representatives, bank officials, or government agents.

How It Typically Happens — Step by Step
Scenario: A first-year engineering student in Pune (name withheld, 2024) lost ₹18,500 through the following sequence:

The Hook: The student posted on a college Facebook group asking if anyone could help with a defective charger purchased online. Within minutes, a scammer posing as a customer care executive from the e-commerce platform contacted her on WhatsApp.
Building Trust: The scammer used the correct company name, a professional-sounding script, and even quoted her recent order details (possibly obtained from public social media or data leaks), making the interaction feel legitimate.
The False Urgency: The scammer said: "We will process your full refund immediately via UPI. Just accept the request on your phone."
The Exploit: The scammer sent a "refund request" link that opened what appeared to be a UPI interface. The victim was asked to enter her UPI PIN to "accept" the refund — a fundamental misunderstanding the scammer deliberately created. In reality, a UPI PIN is only ever required to send money, never to receive it.
The First Debit: ₹9,500 was immediately debited from her account.
The Double Fraud: Panicked, she called the scammer back. The scammer calmly explained the "transaction failed" and asked her to try once more. She did — and lost a further ₹9,000.
Aftermath: The student reported the fraud to cybercrime.gov.in and called Helpline 1930, but the fraudster's account had already been emptied and funds were not recovered.


Who Is Usually Targeted?

First-time UPI users unfamiliar with how the technology works
College students and young adults (trusting, digitally active, but not always security-aware)
Elderly individuals less familiar with digital payments
Anyone who has recently posted publicly about a purchase, complaint, or financial transaction


Consequences

Financial loss — often irreversible once the fraudster withdraws funds
Emotional distress — victims frequently describe feelings of shame, violation, and anxiety
Low recovery rate — Indian cybercrime helplines have limited ability to freeze accounts once funds are withdrawn
Ripple effects — victims may lose trust in digital payments entirely, setting back their financial independence


Source / Basis
This case study is based on a realistic composite of documented UPI fraud patterns reported by:

National Cyber Crime Reporting Portal (cybercrime.gov.in)
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) consumer awareness bulletins
Press Trust of India (PTI) reports on student-targeted UPI scams (2023–2024)
